@John-fk2ky I'm old enough to have been watching the X-Files on the telly, and old enough to remember it wasn't all sunshine and rainbows. Those were great shows and I love them to death, but go back and watch certain episodes and you will see what I mean. I don't mean to belittle these shows, Lost for example is a far worse culprit in terms of fillers and useless episodes, but I just wanted to point out the hypocrisy of the viewers today. Yes, we had a one off episode where the leads don't even meet the characters, but it was a well thought out story and a beatiful episode alltogether, 1 episode in a season of 9. I guarantee you that all those older shows had more than 1/9 of the season filled with fillers and episodes not progressing the main plot at the slightest. 

Furthermore, I for one welcomed when Breaking Bad came about (I'm sure there were earlier examples, but this was the biggest) and broke the stupid notion that all TV shows had to have 24 episodes per season. I would rather watch more different shows with higher quality overall then less filled with fillers and flashbacks just so they could get to the magic number 24.

Not to say there weren't newer shows that had this framework and it worked for them (Person of Interest comes to mind) but they are few and far between.

@janp5063 and then the good shows don't get another season,
so you're left with a show that you enjoyed ending with a cliffhanger and being so unfulfilling that you don't even want to rewatch it.
because why would you, you know it's never going to get concluded.

@buffaloandtrial because you used to have 20 > 24 episodes, so a couple of them being meh wasn't a big deal.
now you have 6 > 8 episodes, so 1 or two of them being filler is taking away a lot of time of the season.

so in modern shows those "fail episodes" are a way bigger fraction of the whole show, and thus way more annoying.

