@willer3399 Exactly. Stranger Things caters to 80s nostalgia. When it came out in 2016, Gen X was 36-51. In the prime of their lives, a big force in the mass cultural zeitgeist. Now, a decade later, Gen X is middle aged to elderly. Even if Season 5 was as good as Season 1, who's going to be left to appreciate it? I'm gen x and I'm not dying anytime soon (that I know of) but I'm increasingly losing interest in new stuff and just working my way through mountains of old media that I'd never seen or seen but forgotten. It feels fresh and new to me. Why bother doomscrolling through whatever Netflix or Prime are pushing on me? 
Mass culture hasn't just moved on, it's disintegrated. The Millennials were the last ones raised with a common base of mass media to form a cultural vocabulary. So we've moved on from the 70s and 80s to references to things like Seinfeld, Friends, the Matrix, Buffy, and Homestar Runner, but that generation is eventually going to age out of media, too. 
That's part of why studios are recycling old franchises, because it's the last common experience they can get a mass audience out of. But when that runs out, there's nothing new to replace it because even the good stuff is too niche.

